When I received the gun it was in pretty bad shape, so I sanded the stock, then stained it a nice red mahogany, and finished it with a varnish, and now it looks like something. The gun is missing one small screw in the front brass but it does not effect how the gun works. It does have dings and Knicks in the wood, but nothing to serious!

I have shot this gun two times using BLACK POWDER because it is a BP ONLY gun. I used 40grs of Goex BP, and shot it both one handed and two handed, and it really doesn't kick too much.

The barrel is starting to get that darkish patina to it, so I would leave it alone. It will only get better

$150obo I know they are some what rare, because this is the first one ive ever handled, and ive handled a lot of vintage, and rare guns in my days. title: For Sale:  M1917 Eddystone WWI Era Battle Rifle
postcontent:
This is an early production (December 1917) M1917 Eddystone in good condition. A must have for any collector

U.S. Model of 1917 Eddystone – with possible original barrel dated 10-17. Good condition all around. Bright, shiny bore – ME is a 1! Battle rear peep site and flip range site – 400 to 1,600 yards. 

The 1903 was the standard US rifle, but when the US got into WW1 in 1917, it was faster to convert the Remington Eddystone plant producing the British Pattern 14 (P14) to 30-06, so they produced the US Model of 1917. Alvin York preferred the 1903, but shot a lot of Germans with the 1917 on the day he earned the CMH. The 1917 was used by more troops than the 1903 in WW1.
